[1]
Date: Sat, 28 Sep 2002 20:11:30 +0100
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: BBC news 28 Sep 2002, 19:05 GMT 20:05 UK [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2286724.stm>
Rabid bat bites woman
----------------------
A woman has been bitten by a bat which has tested positive for a strain of
rabies that can affect humans. The volunteer bat warden has been
vaccinated against the disease after she was bitten on the hand while
caring for the animal on 11 Sep 2002 in north Lancashire.
Initial tests on a Daubenton's bat have proved positive for a strain of
rabies not seen in Britain since 1996, the Department for Environment, Food
and Rural Affairs (Defra) has confirmed. But experts are waiting for the
results of further tests. Five other people who came into contact with the
animal have also received medical treatment.
The strain of rabies, thought to be the most likely virus, is known as EBL
(European bat lyssavirus) [the various serotypes and biotypes of rabies
virus are species classified in the genus _Lyssavirus_; the name is derived
from the Greek "lyssa" meaning rage, fury, madness in dogs. - Mod.CP]. EBL
is a [virus] common in bats across northern Europe and has killed 3 people
in Europe since 1977.
"We have identified 5 other people who had any involvement in the handling
of the bat and are beginning post-exposure treatment. Probably this is over
the top." Dr Frank Atherton, director of public health in Morecambe Bay,
said: "There is no threat to the general public from what has happened in
north Lancashire."
Rare cases
Sick and dead bats, are being sent by conservationists to veterinary
authorities for analysis. It is hoped tests will confirm whether or not
any of the bats are carrying the rabies strain by early next week. Defra
said anyone who finds a sick or ailing bat should not approach or handle it
but should seek advice from a local bat conservation group.
If this case is confirmed it will be the second known case of this strain
of rabies being found in Britain. In June 1996 a pregnant woman and
another woman, were bitten on the hand by a bat carrying the strain.
