<promed@promedmail.org>
[From the press release it appears that the post-exposure treatment of the
bitten person has taken place at least 2 weeks after the alleged incident;
hopefully, there had not been a previous exposure since, from the text, it
is not clear since when the bat had been "looked after". - Mod.AS]
[Rabies is enzootic in all regions of the world except Antartica. However,
several island countries, notably Great Britain, Ireland, Japan, New
Zealand, and Hawaiii, have remained rabies-free once infected animals were
eliminated and strict quarantine and importation regulations applied. Until
1996 Australia was considered rabies-free also, but a novel rabies virus
now designated Australian bat lyssavirus was discovered in Australian bats
and two fatal cases of human infection have been recorded.
The existence of bat rabies in the United Kingdom has been recognised since
1996 when rabies virus was isolated from a single bat among 1800 examined
virologically. The present case is the first indication that rabies virus
can present a risk to people handling bats in the UK. There have been more
than 500 cases of rabies in bats reported in Europe, mostly in Denmark,
Germany, the Netherlands and Russia, and at least three human deaths during
the past two decades. In fact two distinct genotypes of European bat
lyssavirus are recognised. European bat lyssavirus 1 was the genotype
previously isolated in the UK; the genotype of the current isolate has not
been reported.
Genetic characterisation of rabies virus isolates supports the subdivision
of the genus _Lyssavirus_ into 7 distinct genotypes. In the United States
more than half the cases of human rabies investigated between 1976 and 1995
proved to be attributable to bat rabies viruses. The European bat
lyssaviruses belong to genotypes 5 an 6, whereas the North American bat
rabies viruses all belong to genotype 1. African bat lyssaviruses (Lagos
bat virus, Mokola virus and Duvenhage virus) comprise genotypes 2, 3 and 4
respectively, and the Australian bat lyssavirus belongs to genotype 7. It
is presumed that there is sufficient cross-reactivity between the North
American and European bat rabies viruses and the canine rabies virus, from
which the current vaccine is derived, to induce protective immunity. - Mod.CP]
